:::summary
Galileo Galilei (1564–1642) was the Italian physicist, mathematician, and astronomer who transformed humanity's understanding of motion, mechanics, and the cosmos. He improved the telescope and turned it on the night sky, discovered the moons of Jupiter, confirmed the heliocentric theory, and pioneered the experimental method that underlies all modern science. His famous conflict with the Church has been widely misunderstood and caricatured; the truth is far more nuanced and instructive.
:::

